<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><U>2017-2019 PSU Award </U></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The performance metrics and weightings for the 2017-2019 performance cycle are the same as the 2016-2018 performance cycle. The three-year relative TSR metric
is based on our 2017 Peer Group, which was unchanged from the 2016 peer group. The 2017 Peer Group is further described in the section entitled &#147;Setting Compensation.&#148; </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><U>O&#146;Day Special PSU Award </U></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">On May&nbsp;2, 2017, the Compensation Committee approved a special PSU award for Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day. In recognition of his expanded role and overall
accountability for the Company&#146;s supply chain and information technology initiatives, as well as his <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">day-to-day</FONT></FONT> leadership of the Company&#146;s announced Margin
for Growth Program, the Compensation Committee granted Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day 9,341 contingent target PSUs. In general, the PSUs will vest on May&nbsp;2, 2019, the second anniversary of the grant date. The actual number of PSUs earned can range between
0% and 150% of the contingent target PSUs granted to Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day, based on his performance relative to certain individual performance objectives established by the Committee in connection with the award. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">See Column&nbsp;(e) of the 2017 Summary Compensation Table, Columns&nbsp;(f) through&nbsp;(h) of the 2017 Grants of Plan-Based Awards Table, Columns&nbsp;(i)
and&nbsp;(j) of the Outstanding Equity Awards at 2017 Fiscal-Year End Table and Columns&nbsp;(d) and&nbsp;(e) of the 2017 Option Exercises and Stock Vested Table for more information about PSUs awarded to the NEOs. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><I>Stock Options </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Stock options
are an important element of our long-term incentive program, enabling us to align the interests of NEOs with those of stockholders. In general, stock options are awarded annually to the Company&#146;s executives as well as to other key managerial
employees. Stock options entitle the holder to purchase a fixed number of shares of Common Stock at a set price during a specified period of time. The right to exercise the options is subject to a vesting schedule. Because stock options vest over
time and only have value if the price of our Common Stock increases, they encourage efforts to enhance long-term stockholder value. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation
Committee sets guidelines for the value of stock options to be awarded based on competitive compensation data. The stock option award represents approximately <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-quarter</FONT> of the NEO&#146;s long-term incentive
compensation target award. In 2017, the target number of stock options awarded to each NEO was determined by multiplying the NEO&#146;s base salary by <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-quarter</FONT> of his or her target long-term incentive award
percentage divided by the Black-Scholes value of each option on the grant date. The Black-Scholes option-pricing model is described in Note&nbsp;10 to the Consolidated Financial Statements contained in the 2017 Annual Report on Form <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> that accompanies this Proxy Statement. The actual number of options awarded may vary from the target level based on each NEO&#146;s individual performance evaluation. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Stock options vest in equal increments over four years and have a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-year</FONT> term. As required by the EICP, the options
have an exercise price equal to the closing market price of the Common Stock on the NYSE on the date of the award. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">See Column&nbsp;(f) of the 2017 Summary
Compensation Table, Columns&nbsp;(j) through (l)&nbsp;of the 2017 Grants of Plan-Based Awards Table, Columns&nbsp;(b) through (f)&nbsp;of the Outstanding Equity Awards at 2017 Fiscal-Year End Table and Columns&nbsp;(b) and (c)&nbsp;of the 2017
Option Exercises and Stock Vested Table for more information on stock options awarded to the NEOs. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">57 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><I>Restricted Stock Units </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation Committee sets guidelines for the value of the annual RSUs to be awarded based on competitive compensation data. These RSU awards represent
approximately <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-quarter</FONT> of the NEO&#146;s long-term incentive compensation target award. In 2017, the target number of RSUs awarded to each NEO was determined by multiplying the NEO&#146;s base salary by <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-quarter</FONT> of his or her target long-term incentive award percentage divided by the closing price of the Company&#146;s Common Stock on the NYSE on the grant date. The actual number of RSUs awarded may vary from
the target level based on each NEO&#146;s individual performance evaluation. Annual RSUs vest in equal increments over three years. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation
Committee also awards RSUs to NEOs and other executives from time to time as special incentives. RSUs also are awarded by the Compensation Committee to replace compensation forfeited by newly-hired executive officers and by the CEO to employees
other than executive officers from the RSU pool described below. Mr.&nbsp;Tillemans and Ms.&nbsp;West were each granted RSUs upon their hire to replace forfeited compensation from their prior employers. These replacement RSU awards vest in equal
increments over three years. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">See Column (e)&nbsp;of the 2017 Summary Compensation Table, Column (i)&nbsp;of the 2017 Grants of Plan-Based Awards Table,
Columns (g)&nbsp;and (h)&nbsp;of the Outstanding Equity Awards at 2017 Fiscal-Year End Table and Columns (d)&nbsp;and (e)&nbsp;of the 2017 Option Exercises and Stock Vested Table for more information about RSUs awarded to the NEOs. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><I>Equity Pools </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">To ensure
flexibility in providing awards for recruitment, retention, performance recognition or in conjunction with a promotion, the Compensation Committee is authorized under the EICP to establish a stock option pool, a PSU pool, a RSU pool and a separate
CEO discretionary equity pool for use by our CEO for such purposes. The pools are available for approximately 12 months from the date created. The Compensation Committee determines whether to establish any or all of these pools annually. Options,
PSUs and RSUs remaining in any pool at the end of the period do not carry over to pools established for a subsequent period. The CEO may not make discretionary awards from any pool to the NEOs. Awards from the CEO pools and the CEO discretionary
equity pool are made monthly according to an annually <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-determined</FONT> schedule. The exercise price for the options is based on the closing price of our Common Stock on the date of the award. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><B><A NAME="toc498129_26"></A>Perquisites </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Executive perquisites are kept to a minimal level
relative to a NEO&#146;s total compensation and do not play a significant role in our executive compensation program. The perquisites that we provide, include personal use of Company aircraft, security services for our CEO, and financial counseling
and tax preparation reimbursement. See the footnotes to Column&nbsp;(i) of the 2017 Summary Compensation Table for information regarding the perquisites received by our NEOs. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Our CEO and the other NEOs are eligible to participate in our Gift Matching Program on the same basis as other employees, retirees or their spouses. Through
the Gift Matching Program, we match contributions made to one or more <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-profit</FONT> organizations on a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">dollar-for-dollar</FONT></FONT> basis up to
a maximum aggregate contribution of $5,000 per employee annually. These matching contributions are not considered compensation and are not included in Column&nbsp;(i) of the 2017 Summary Compensation Table. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">58 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><B><A NAME="toc498129_27"></A>Retirement Plans </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">NEOs participate in our
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> defined benefit pension plan (&#147;pension plan&#148;) and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> defined contribution 401(k) plan (&#147;401(k) plan&#148;) on the same basis as
other salaried employees of the Company. IRC regulations do not permit the Company to use base salary and other compensation paid above certain limits to determine the benefits earned by the NEOs under
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> plans. The Company maintains a defined benefit Supplemental Executive Retirement Plan (&#147;DB&nbsp;SERP&#148;), a defined contribution Supplemental Executive Retirement Plan
(&#147;DC&nbsp;SERP&#148;) and a Deferred Compensation Plan to provide these and additional benefits that are comparable to those offered by our peers. Under the provisions of the Deferred Compensation Plan, our NEOs may elect to defer payments from
the OHIP, PSU and RSU awards, but not stock options or base salary. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The DB&nbsp;SERP was closed to new participants in 2006. No new participants have been
or will be added to the DB&nbsp;SERP. NEOs and other senior executives reporting to the CEO not eligible for the DB&nbsp;SERP are considered by the Compensation Committee for participation in the DC&nbsp;SERP. In comparison, the DC&nbsp;SERP
typically yields a lower benefit than the DB&nbsp;SERP upon retirement. The Company believes that the DB&nbsp;SERP, DC&nbsp;SERP and Deferred Compensation Plan help, in the aggregate, to attract and retain executive talent, as similar plans are
often components of the executive compensation programs within our peer group. The DC&nbsp;SERP was established as part of our Deferred Compensation Plan and is not a separate plan. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">See the 2017 Pension Benefits Table and accompanying narrative and the 2017 <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-Qualified</FONT> Deferred Compensation Table
and accompanying narrative for more information regarding the DB&nbsp;SERP, DC&nbsp;
SERP and other retirement benefits. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><B><A NAME="toc498129_28"></A>Employment Agreements </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Company entered into an employment agreement with
Ms.&nbsp;Buck in February 2017, which provides for Ms.&nbsp;Buck&#146;s continued employment as President and CEO and continued nomination as a member of the Board of Directors. The employment agreement does not have a specified term. Under the
terms of the employment agreement, in the event Ms.&nbsp;Buck&#146;s employment is terminated by the Company without Cause or she resigns for Good Reason (in each case as defined in the employment agreement), Ms.&nbsp;Buck will be entitled to
certain severance benefits. In the event of her termination after a change in control, Ms.&nbsp;Buck will be eligible to receive benefits under the Executive Benefits Protection Plan (Group 3A) (&#147;EBPP&nbsp;3A&#148;). She is not entitled to an
excise tax <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">gross-up.</FONT> The employment agreement subjects Ms.&nbsp;Buck to certain <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-competition</FONT> and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-solicitation</FONT> covenants
under the ECRCA and to compensation recovery (clawback) to the extent required by applicable law and regulations. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">See the section entitled &#147;Potential
Payments upon Termination or Change in Control&#148; for information regarding the payments Ms.&nbsp;Buck would receive in the event of an applicable termination or change in control occurring on December&nbsp;31, 2017. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In August 2012, the Company entered into an employment agreement with Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey, the terms of which were substantially similar to the terms of
Ms.&nbsp;Buck&#146;s employment agreement. Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey retired as our President and CEO effective March&nbsp;1, 2017. In connection with his retirement, the Company and Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey entered into a retirement agreement (&#147;Retirement
Agreement&#148;) in February 2017 in order to set forth the benefits Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey received in connection with his retirement. The Retirement Agreement superseded and replaced Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey&#146;s employment agreement. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Other than as set forth above, we have not entered into employment agreements with any NEO. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">59 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><B><A NAME="toc498129_29"></A>Severance and Change in Control Plans </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">All of the NEOs are covered by our EBPP 3A. The
EBPP&nbsp;3A is intended to help us attract and retain executive talent and maintain a stable work environment in the event of activity that could potentially result in a Change in Control. The severance protection provided under the EBPP&nbsp;3A
upon a Change in Control is based upon a &#147;double trigger.&#148; The terms of the plan generally provide that a covered NEO whose employment with the Company terminates in qualifying circumstances within two years after a Change in Control of
the Company is entitled to certain severance payments and benefits. The EBPP&nbsp;3A also provides severance benefits in the event of involuntary termination without Cause unrelated to a Change in Control or voluntary termination for Good Reason
within two years after election of a new CEO. Change in Control, Cause and Good Reason are defined in the EBPP&nbsp;3A. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">See the discussion in the section
entitled &#147;Potential Payments upon Termination or Change in Control&#148; for information regarding the payments that would be due to our NEOs under the EBPP 3A in the event of an applicable termination of employment or a Change in Control. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><B><A NAME="toc498129_30"></A>Compensation Policies and Practices </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><I>Clawbacks </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Under the EICP, when an individual&#146;s actions result in the filing of financial documents not in compliance with financial reporting requirements, the
Company has the right to recoup or require repayment of an award earned or accrued during the twelve-month period following the first public issuance or filing with the SEC of the financial document not in compliance with such financial reporting
requirement. Repayment or clawback occurs where the material noncompliance results from misconduct, the participant&#146;s knowledge or gross negligence in engaging in the misconduct or failing to prevent the misconduct, or if the participant is one
of the individuals subject to automatic forfeiture under Section&nbsp;304 of the Sarbanes-Oxley Action of 2002. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In 2008, the Company initiated the
execution of the ECRCA by executive officers as a condition for the receipt of long-term incentive awards and, for new executive officers, also as a condition of employment. The purpose of the ECRCA is to protect the Company and further align the
interests of the executive officer with those of the Company. The terms of the ECRCA prohibit the executive from misusing or disclosing the Company&#146;s confidential information, competing with the Company in specific categories for a period of
12&nbsp;months following separation from employment, recruiting or soliciting the Company&#146;s employees, or disparaging the Company&#146;s reputation in any way. For those officers or employees based outside the U.S., the restrictive covenants
and terms may be modified to comply with local laws. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Failure to comply with the provisions of the ECRCA may result in cancellation of the unvested portion
of PSU and RSU awards, cancellation of any unexercised stock options and a requirement for repayment of amounts received from equity awards during the last year of employment, as well as any amounts received from the DB&nbsp;SERP or DC&nbsp;SERP.
</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><I>Tax Considerations </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">As
in effect through the end of our fiscal year ended December&nbsp;31, 2017, Section&nbsp;162(m) of the IRC generally disallowed the Company&#146;s ability to deduct compensation in excess of $1&nbsp;million paid to our CEO or to our other NEOs who
are employed on the last day of the fiscal year (other than officers who served as CFO during the year), but did not disallow a deduction for compensation that qualifies as &#147;performance-based&#148; under applicable Internal Revenue Service
(&#147;IRS&#148;) regulations or that is paid after termination of employment. As a result of changes to Section&nbsp;162(m) of the Code resulting from federal legislation referred to as the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act, the $1.0&nbsp;million deduction
limitation described above will be expanded to disallow the deduction for compensation payable to a larger group of employees, effective for tax years beginning after December&nbsp;31, 2017. Performance-based compensation, including equity awards,
will no longer be exempt from the 162(m) deduction limitation, </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">60 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">
subject to certain transition rules, and the employees (referred to as &#147;covered employees&#148;) to whom the deduction limitation will apply include the CEO and CFO (in each case, whether or
not serving as executive officers as of the end of the fiscal year) and the three other most highly compensated executive officers. In addition, once considered a &#147;covered employee&#148; for a given year, the individual will be treated as a
&#147;covered employee&#148; for all subsequent years. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation Committee has considered the effect of Section&nbsp;162(m) of the IRC on the
Company&#146;s executive compensation program. The Compensation Committee exercises discretion in setting base salaries, structuring incentive compensation awards and in determining payments in relation to levels of achievement of performance goals.
The Compensation Committee believes that the total compensation program for NEOs should be managed in accordance with the objectives outlined in the Company&#146;s compensation philosophy and in the best overall interests of the Company&#146;s
stockholders. Accordingly, compensation paid by the Company may not be deductible because such compensation exceeds the limitations, or does not meet the &#147;performance-based&#148; or other requirements, for deductibility under
Section&nbsp;162(m) of the IRC. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Section&nbsp;409A of the IRC specifies certain rules and limitations regarding the operation of our Deferred Compensation
Plan and other retirement programs. Failure to comply with these rules could subject participants in those plans and programs to additional income tax and interest penalties. We believe our plans and programs comply with Section&nbsp;409A of the
IRC. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><B><A NAME="toc498129_31"></A>Stock Ownership Guidelines </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation Committee believes that requiring
NEOs and other executive officers to hold significant amounts of our Common Stock strengthens their alignment with the interest of our stockholders and promotes achievement of long-term business objectives. Our executive stock ownership policy has
been in place for more than 20 years. The Compensation Committee reviews ownership requirements annually to ensure they are aligned with external market comparisons. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Executives with stock ownership requirements have five years from their initial election to their position to accumulate and hold the minimum number of shares
required. For purposes of this requirement, &#147;shares&#148; include shares of our Common Stock that are owned by the executive, unvested time-based RSUs, PSUs earned for the annual segments of open performance cycles and vested RSUs and PSUs that
have been deferred by the executive as Common Stock units under our Deferred Compensation Plan. It is anticipated that executives will hold a significant number of the shares earned from PSU and RSU awards and the exercise of stock options to
satisfy their obligations. Minimum stockholding requirements for the CEO and the other NEOs are as follows: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="84%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">

executives subject to stockholding requirements</P> <P STYLE="font-size:1pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt">&nbsp;</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #3f000b; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #3f000b" ALIGN="center"> 1 times base salary<P STYLE="font-size:1pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt" align="left">&nbsp;</P></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The dollar value of shares which must be acquired and held equals a multiple of the individual executive&#146;s base salary.
Stockholding requirements are updated whenever a change in base salary occurs. Failure to reach the minimum within the five-year period results in a notification letter to the executive, with a copy to the CEO, and a requirement that future stock
option exercises, RSU distributions and PSU payments be settled by retaining at least 50% of the shares of Common Stock received until the minimum ownership level is attained. The Compensation Committee receives an annual summary of each individual
executive&#146;s ownership status to monitor compliance. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">61 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><B><A NAME="toc498129_32"></A>COMPENSATION COMMITTEE REPORT
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" COLOR="#3f000b">To Our Stockholders:</FONT> </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">We have reviewed and discussed with management the Compensation Discussion&nbsp;&amp; Analysis. Based on that review and discussion, we have recommended to the
Board of Directors that the Compensation Discussion&nbsp;&amp; Analysis be included in this Proxy Statement. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Submitted by the Compensation and Executive
Organization Committee of the Board of Directors: </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:54%; text-indent:-2%; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">James M. Mead, Chair </P>

<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(1)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey was Chairman of the Board, President and CEO through February&nbsp;28, 2017, retiring from the position of President and CEO on March&nbsp;1, 2017. Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey continues to serve as <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-executive</FONT> Chairman of the Board. Ms.&nbsp;Buck served as Executive Vice President, COO until March&nbsp;1, 2017, when she was promoted to President and CEO. On May&nbsp;2, 2017, Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day was appointed
Senior Vice President, Chief Product Supply and Technology Officer. Previously, he served as the Senior Vice President, Chief Supply Chain Officer. On April&nbsp;3, 2017, Mr.&nbsp;Tillemans was hired as President, U.S. and on May&nbsp;1, 2017,
Ms.&nbsp;West was hired as Senior Vice President, Chief Growth Officer. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(2)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Column (c)&nbsp;reflects base salary earned, on an accrual basis, for the years indicated and includes IRC Section&nbsp;125 deductions pursuant to The Hershey Company Flexible Benefits Plan and amounts deferred by the
NEOs in accordance with the provisions of the 401(k) plan. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(3)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">With the exception of Mr.&nbsp;Tillemans and Ms.&nbsp;West, Column (d)&nbsp;indicates that no discretionary bonuses were paid to the NEOs in 2017, 2016 or 2015. Mr.&nbsp;Tillemans and Ms.&nbsp;West, who joined the
Company in April 2017 and May 2017, respectively, each received a cash <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">sign-on</FONT> bonus to replace awards forfeited at their prior employers. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(4)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Column (e)&nbsp;shows the aggregate grant date fair value of RSUs and contingent target PSU awards granted to the NEOs in the years indicated. The assumptions used to determine the grant date fair value of awards listed
in Column (e)&nbsp;are set forth in Note 10 to the Company&#146;s Consolidated Financial Statements included in our 2017 Annual Report on Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> that accompanies this Proxy Statement. The amounts in Column
(e)&nbsp;do not reflect the value of shares actually received or which may be received in the future with respect to such awards. </TD></TR></TABLE>

forfeited a prorated portion of his 2017 RSU grant, the value of which is included in Column&nbsp;(e) of the 2017 Summary Compensation Table. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(5)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Column (f)&nbsp;presents the grant date fair value of stock options awarded to the NEOs for the years indicated and does not reflect the value of shares actually received or which may be received in the future with
respect to such stock options. The assumptions we made to determine the value of these awards are set forth in Note 10 to the Company&#146;s Consolidated Financial Statements included in our 2017 Annual Report on Form
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> that accompanies this Proxy Statement. The number of stock options awarded to each NEO during 2017 appears in Column (j)&nbsp;of the 2017 Grants of Plan-Based Awards Table. As a result of his retirement
on March&nbsp;1, 2017, Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey forfeited a prorated portion of his 2017 stock option grant, the value of which is included in Column&nbsp;(e) of the 2017 Summary Compensation Table. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(6)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Column (g)&nbsp;reflects the OHIP payments made to each NEO based upon actual salary received in 2017. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(7)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Column (h)&nbsp;reflects the aggregate change in the actuarial present value of the NEO&#146;s retirement benefit under the Company&#146;s pension plan and the DB SERP. The change in value calculation uses the same
discount rate and mortality rate assumptions as the 2016 and 2017 audited financial statements, as applicable, and measures the change in value between the pension plan measurement date in the 2016 and 2017 audited financial statements. The change
in value during a year is primarily driven by three factors: 1) changes in valuation assumptions; 2) changes in the NEO&#146;s pensionable earnings; and 3) an additional year of service and age. During 2016 and 2017, each of the three factors
driving change caused a minor increase to the pension value. The impact when combining each of the three minor increases resulted in a relatively larger increase to the pension value. The amounts in Column (h)&nbsp;do not reflect amounts paid or
that might be paid to the NEO. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Mmes. Little and West and Messrs.&nbsp;O&#146;Day and Tillemans participate in the DC&nbsp;SERP rather than the DB&nbsp;SERP. The DC&nbsp;SERP is established under the Company&#146;s Deferred Compensation Plan.
DC&nbsp;SERP contributions for Mmes. Little and West and Messrs.&nbsp;O&#146;Day and Tillemans are included in Column&nbsp;(i) as explained in more detail in footnote&nbsp;(8) below. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">The NEOs also participate in our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-qualified,</FONT> <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-funded</FONT> Deferred Compensation Plan under which deferred amounts are credited with
notional earnings based on the performance of one or more third-party investment options available to all participants in our 401(k) plan. No portion of the notional earnings credited during 2017 was &#147;above market&#148; or
&#147;preferential.&#148; Consequently, no Deferred Compensation Plan earnings are included in amounts reported in Column&nbsp;(h)&nbsp;above. See the 2017 Pension Benefits Table and the 2017 <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-Qualified</FONT>
Deferred Compensation Table for more information on the benefits payable to the NEOs under the pension plan, DB&nbsp;SERP and Deferred Compensation Plan. </TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">64 </P>

</DIV></Center>

<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #3f000b" ALIGN="right"> &#151;<P STYLE="font-size:2pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt" align="left">&nbsp;</P></TD>

<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #3f000b" ALIGN="right"> &#151;<P STYLE="font-size:2pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt" align="left">&nbsp;</P></TD>
<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #3f000b; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #3f000b; padding-right:2pt"> &nbsp;<P STYLE="font-size:2pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt">&nbsp;</P></TD></TR>
</TABLE></DIV> <P STYLE="line-height:8.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;margin-left:3%;border-bottom:1.00pt solid #000000; width:21%">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(a)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Employees who earn over the IRS compensation limit and/or defer any portion of their OHIP award are eligible for the Supplemental 401(k) Match, contingent on the employee contributing an amount to the 401(k) plan equal
to the annual <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-tax</FONT> limit established by the IRS. Mmes. Buck, Little and West and Messrs. O&#146;Day and Tillemans are eligible to receive a Supplemental 401(k) Match Contribution equal to 4.5% of the amount
by which their eligible earnings (salary and OHIP) exceeds the IRS compensation limit. For 2016 and 2015, Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey was eligible to receive a Supplemental 401(k) Match Contribution equal to 4.5% of the amount by which his eligible earnings
(salary and OHIP) exceeded the IRS compensation limit. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(b)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">As are all new hires of the Company since January&nbsp;1, 2007, Mmes. Little and West and Messrs. O&#146;Day and Tillemans are eligible to receive a contribution to their 401(k) plan account equal to 3% of base salary
and OHIP up to the maximum amount permitted by the IRS. We call this contribution the Core Retirement Contribution (&#147;CRC&#148;). They also are eligible to receive a Supplemental Core Retirement Contribution (&#147;Supplemental CRC&#148;) equal
to 3% of the amount by which their eligible earnings (salary and OHIP) exceeds the IRS compensation limit. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(c)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">The value of any personal use of Company aircraft by the NEOs is based on the Company&#146;s aggregate incremental <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">per-flight</FONT> hour cost for the aircraft used and flight time of
the applicable flight. The incremental <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">per-flight</FONT> hour cost is calculated by reference to fuel, maintenance (labor and parts), crew, landing and parking expenses. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(d)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">From time to time the Company provided security services to Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey when the Company determined that conditions warranted such services for the safety and protection of Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey and his family. The
amount reported is the Company&#146;s incremental cost for such services. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(e)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Mr.&nbsp;Tillemans and Ms.&nbsp;West joined the Company in 2017 and each received Company relocation benefits totaling $297,960 and $117,080, respectively, for shipment of household goods, temporary living assistance
and miscellaneous allowances, home finding trips and assistance in purchasing their new residences, Mr.&nbsp;Tillemans and Ms.&nbsp;West also each received a net tax gross up totaling $196,633 and $66,423, respectively, to offset the amounts imputed
to their income as a result of these benefits. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(f)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Reflects attorney fees paid or incurred in connection with the negotiation of Ms.&nbsp;Buck&#146;s employment agreement and Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey&#146;s Retirement Agreement. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="4%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(g)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Reflects $3,012,779 paid to Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey under his Retirement Agreement as a DB SERP-equivalent payment. For purposes of calculating this DB SERP-equivalent payment, Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey was deemed to have retired on
July&nbsp;1, 2017 and to have completed 1,000 &#147;hours of service&#148; under the DB SERP in 2017 (as such term is defined in the DB SERP). In addition, reflects a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">gross-up</FONT> payment of $270,080 in order to
provide Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey with benefits equivalent to what would have been provided had the payment been made under the DB SERP. </TD></TR></TABLE>

<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(2)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Except for Mr.&nbsp;Tillemans and Ms.&nbsp;West, Columns (c), (d) and (e)&nbsp;represent the threshold, target and maximum potential amounts that each NEO had the opportunity to earn based on the OHIP targets approved
for the NEOs in February 2017 and adjusted for Ms.&nbsp;Buck and Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day&#146;s target changes in March 2017 and May 2017, respectively. For Mr.&nbsp;Tillemans and Ms.&nbsp;West, Columns (c), (d) and (e)&nbsp;represent the threshold,
target and maximum potential amounts that each NEO had the opportunity to earn based on the OHIP targets approved for the NEOs upon their respective hire dates. All amounts shown in Columns (c), (d) and (e)&nbsp;are based upon actual salary received
in 2017. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">The threshold amount is the amount that would have been payable had the minimum individual performance score been achieved and the Company performance score been zero. The target amount is the amount that would have
been payable had the Company and individual performance scores been 100% on all metrics. The maximum amount is the amount that would have been payable had the maximum score been achieved on all metrics. </TD></TR></TABLE>

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(3)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Columns (f), (g) and (h)&nbsp;represent the number of threshold, target and maximum potential PSUs that can be earned for the 2017-2019 performance cycle and, with the exception of Mr.&nbsp;Tillemans and Ms.&nbsp;West,
the 2017 adjusted earnings per share-diluted component of the 2015-2017 performance cycle. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Each PSU represents the value of one share of our Common Stock. The number of PSUs earned for the 2017-2019 performance cycle and for the 2017 adjusted earnings&nbsp;per&nbsp;share-diluted component of the 2015-2017
performance cycle will depend upon achievement against the metrics explained in the Compensation Discussion&nbsp;&amp; Analysis in the section entitled &#147;Performance Stock Unit Targets and Results.&#148; </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Payment, if any, will be made in shares of the Company&#146;s Common Stock at the conclusion of the three-year performance cycle. The Compensation Committee approved the targets for the annual adjusted
earnings&nbsp;per&nbsp;share-diluted metrics at the beginning of each of the three years in the performance cycle. The minimum award as shown in Column&nbsp;(f)&nbsp;is the number of shares payable for achievement of the threshold level of
performance on one of the metrics and the maximum award as shown in Column&nbsp;(h) is the number of shares payable for achievement of the maximum level of performance on all metrics. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">For Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day, Columns (f), (g) and (h)&nbsp;also include the number of threshold, target and maximum potential PSUs that can be earned for his special PSU award. Each PSU represents the value of one share of
our Common Stock. The number of PSUs earned for this special award will depend upon achievement against the metrics explained in the Compensation Discussion&nbsp;&amp; Analysis in the section entitled &#147;Performance Stock Unit Targets and
Results.&#148; Payment, if any, will be made in shares of the Company&#146;s Common Stock at the conclusion of the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">two-year</FONT> performance cycle. The minimum award as shown in Column (f)&nbsp;is the number of
shares payable for achievement of the threshold level of performance on one of the metrics and the maximum award as shown in Column (h)&nbsp;is the number of shares payable for achievement of the maximum level of performance on all metrics.
</TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">More information regarding PSUs and the 2017 awards can be found in the Compensation Discussion&nbsp;&amp; Analysis and the Outstanding Equity Awards at 2017 Fiscal-Year End Table. </TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">66 </P>

<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(4)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">For each NEO, Column (i)&nbsp;represents the number of annual RSUs granted to Messrs. Bilbrey and O&#146;Day and Ms.&nbsp;Little on February&nbsp;22, 2017, Ms.&nbsp;Buck on March&nbsp;1, 2017, Mr.&nbsp;Tillemans on
April&nbsp;3, 2017 and Ms.&nbsp;West on May&nbsp;1, 2017. Target RSU awards were determined by multiplying <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-quarter</FONT> of the executive&#146;s long-term incentive target percentage times his or her 2017 base
salary, divided by the closing price of the Company&#146;s Common Stock on the NYSE on the award date as shown in Column (k). Except for Mr.&nbsp;Tillemans and Ms.&nbsp;West, the actual number of RSUs awarded varied from the target level based on
the executive&#146;s performance evaluation for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016. Annual RSU awards vest in thirds over three years. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>

These RSU awards will vest in thirds over three years. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

</TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

target percentage times his or her 2017 base salary, divided by the Black-Scholes value of (i) $15.75 per option for Messrs. Bilbrey and O&#146;Day and Ms.&nbsp;Little, (ii)&nbsp;$16.11 per option for Ms.&nbsp;Buck, (iii)&nbsp;$15.72 per option for
Mr.&nbsp;Tillemans and (iiii)&nbsp;$15.37 per option for Ms.&nbsp;West. The Black-Scholes value is based on the option exercise price, which is equal to the closing price of the Company&#146;s Common Stock on the NYSE on the award date. Except for
Mr.&nbsp;Tillemans and Ms.&nbsp;West, the actual number of options awarded varied from the target level based on the executive&#146;s performance evaluation for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

each performance cycle and may be fewer or more than the number reflected in Column (i). Column (j)&nbsp;sets forth the value of PSUs reported in Column (i)&nbsp;using the $113.51 closing price per share of our Common Stock on the NYSE on

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(2)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">For Mmes. Buck and Little and Messrs. Bilbrey and O&#146;Day, the first number in Column (d), includes the number of PSUs earned from the 2015-2017 performance cycle that ended on December&nbsp;31, 2017, as determined
by the Compensation Committee, or, in the case of Ms.&nbsp;Buck and Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey, by the independent members of our Board. The aggregate results of the 2015-2017 performance cycle exceeded the financial thresholds, but did not meet the financial
targets, established at the start of the performance cycle; therefore, the number of PSUs included in Column (d)&nbsp;reflects payment at 19.54% of target. All of the applicable NEOs received payment of the award in Common Stock in February 2018. In
accordance with the terms of the PSU award agreement, each PSU represents one share of our Common Stock valued in Column (e)&nbsp;at $99.90 the closing price of our Common Stock on the NYSE on February&nbsp;20, 2018, the date the Compensation
Committee approved the PSU payment. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(3)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">For Mmes. Buck and Little and Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day, the second number in Column (d)&nbsp;reflects annual RSUs that were distributed in 2017 from the 2016 award and the number in Column (e)&nbsp;sets forth the value of
such RSUs at vesting on March&nbsp;16, 2017 and cash credits equivalent to dividends accrued during the vesting period. Ms.&nbsp;Little elected to defer 100% of this award. As a result, on the vesting date of these RSUs, because the cash credits
earned for the 1,332 shares deferred did not exceed the tax liability associated with those shares, 10 shares were liquidated to cover the tax liability. The remaining 1,322 shares were credited to Ms.&nbsp;Little&#146;s Deferred Compensation
account and she received a cash payment for the remaining liquidated share value (less cash withheld to meet tax obligations). </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(4)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">For Ms.&nbsp;Little, the second number in Column (d)&nbsp;also reflects RSUs that were distributed in 2017 from a 2015 award and the number in Column (e)&nbsp;sets forth the value of such RSUs at vesting on
April&nbsp;15, 2017 and cash credits equivalent to dividends accrued during the vesting period. Ms.&nbsp;Little elected to defer 100% of this award. Because the cash credits earned for the 4,136 shares deferred exceeded the tax liability associated
with those shares, the 4,136 shares were credited to Ms.&nbsp;Little&#146;s Deferred Compensation account and she received a cash payment for the remaining dividend value (less cash withheld to meet tax obligations). </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">For Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day, the second number in Column (d)&nbsp;also reflects retention RSUs that were distributed in 2017 and the number in Column (e)&nbsp;sets forth the value of such RSUs at vesting on June&nbsp;15,
2017 and cash credits equivalent to dividends accrued during the vesting period. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(6)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">For Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey, the second number in Column (d)&nbsp;reflects annual RSUs that were distributed in 2017 in connection with his retirement and the number in Column (e)&nbsp;sets forth the value of such RSUs at
vesting on September&nbsp;1, 2017 and cash credits equivalent to dividends accrued during the vesting period. These amounts are further described in the section entitled &#147;Separation Payments under Retirement Agreement.&#148; </TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">70 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><B><A NAME="toc498129_37"></A>2017 Pension Benefits Table </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Ms.&nbsp;Buck is a participant in our pension plan and
is fully vested in benefits under that plan. Ms.&nbsp;Buck is also eligible to participate in our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-qualified</FONT> DB&nbsp;SERP. No benefit is payable under the DB&nbsp;SERP if the executive officer terminates
employment prior to age 55 or if he or she does not have five years of service with the Company. As of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2017, Ms.&nbsp;Buck had attained age 55 with five years of service and therefore was fully vested in her DB SERP benefit.
Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey was also a participant in our pension and DB SERP plans prior to his retirement. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The combination of the pension and DB&nbsp;SERP plans
was designed to provide a benefit upon retirement at or after reaching age 60 based on a joint and survivor annuity equal to 55% of final average compensation for an executive with 15 or more years of service (reduced pro rata for each year of
service under 15). Effective January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2007, the benefit payable under the DB&nbsp;SERP to an executive who was age 50 or over as of January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2007, was reduced by 10%, and the benefit payable to an executive who had not
attained age 50 as of January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2007, was reduced by 20%. As a result, the benefit payable to Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey was reduced by 10% and the benefit payable to Ms.&nbsp;Buck was reduced by 20%. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Under the terms of the DB SERP, final average compensation is calculated as the sum of (i)&nbsp;the average of the highest three calendar years of base salary
paid over the last five years of employment with the Company and (ii)&nbsp;the average of the highest three OHIP awards, paid or deferred, for the last five years of employment with the Company. The benefit accrued under the DB&nbsp;SERP is payable
upon retirement (subject to the provisions of Section&nbsp;409A of the IRC) as a lump sum or a life annuity with 50% benefit continuation to the participant&#146;s surviving spouse, or payment may be deferred in accordance with the provisions of the
Company&#146;s Deferred Compensation Plan. The lump sum is equal to the actuarial present value of the joint and survivor pension earned, reduced by the lump sum value of the benefits to be paid under the pension plan and the value of the
executive&#146;s Social Security benefits. If the executive terminates employment after age 55 but before age 60, the benefit is reduced for early retirement at a rate of 5%&nbsp;per year for the period until the executive would have turned 60. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">On November&nbsp;16, 2015, the Company and Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey entered into an amendment to his existing employment agreement, the effect of which was to
increase, from five to ten years, the duration of the look-back period for selecting the highest three years of base salary and annual incentive payment used to calculate Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey&#146;s final average compensation for determining his benefit
under the DB SERP. The amendment also established the interest rate to be applied to the calculation of amounts payable to Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey under the DB SERP as the rate equal to the Lump Sum Interest Rate (as defined in the DB SERP) as of
October&nbsp;31, 2015. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">71 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

accrued under the pension plan and the DB&nbsp;SERP, as applicable, for each NEO as of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2017. The amounts shown for the DB&nbsp;SERP reflect the reduction for the present value of the benefits under the pension plan and Social
Security benefits. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(2)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">These amounts were paid to Mr.&nbsp;
Bilbrey from the pension plan and DB SERP. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><B><A NAME="toc498129_38"></A>2017
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-Qualified</FONT> Deferred Compensation Table </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Our NEOs are eligible to participate in the Company&#146;s Deferred Compensation Plan. The Deferred Compensation Plan is a
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-qualified,</FONT> <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-funded</FONT> plan that permits participants to defer compensation that would otherwise be paid to them currently. The Deferred Compensation Plan is intended
to secure the goodwill and loyalty of participants by enabling them to defer compensation when the participants deem it beneficial to do so and by providing a vehicle for the Company to make, on a
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-qualified</FONT> basis, contributions that could not be made on the participants&#146; behalf to the 401(k) plan. The Company credits the Deferred Compensation Plan with a specified percentage of compensation for
NEOs participating in the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-qualified</FONT> DC&nbsp;SERP. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">72 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Our NEOs may elect to defer payments to be received from the OHIP, PSU and RSU awards, but not stock options
or base salary. Amounts deferred under the DB SERP, DC SERP, OHIP, PSU and RSU awards are fully vested and are credited to the individual&#146;s account under the Deferred Compensation Plan. Participants elect to receive payment at termination of
employment or some other future date. DB&nbsp;SERP payments designated for deferral into the Deferred Compensation Plan are not credited as earned but are credited in full upon the participant&#146;s retirement. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Payments are distributed in a lump sum or in annual installments for up to 15 years. All amounts are payable in a lump sum following a Change in Control (as
such terms is defined in the EICP). All elections and payments under the Deferred Compensation Plan are subject to compliance with Section&nbsp;409A of the IRC, which may limit elections and require a delay in payment of benefits in certain
circumstances. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">While deferred, amounts are credited with notional earnings as if they were invested by the participant in one or more investment options
offered by the Deferred Compensation Plan. The investment options under the Deferred Compensation Plan consist of investment in a deferred common stock unit account that we value according to the performance of our Common Stock (for awards paid in
stock) or in mutual funds or other investments available to participants in our 401(k) plan (for awards paid in cash). The participants&#146; accounts under the Deferred Compensation Plan fluctuate daily, depending upon performance of the investment
options elected. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Effective January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2007, we began crediting the deferred compensation accounts of all employees, including the NEOs, with the
amount of employer matching contributions that exceed the limits established by the IRS for contribution to the 401(k) plan. These amounts are credited in the first quarter of the year after they are earned. As shown in the footnotes to the 2017
Summary Compensation Table, these amounts are designated as &#147;Supplemental 401(k) Match&#148; and are included as &#147;All Other Compensation&#148; in the year earned. These amounts also are included in Column&nbsp;(c) of the 2017 <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-Qualified</FONT> Deferred Compensation Table in the year earned. With the exception of Mr.&nbsp;Tillemans and Ms.&nbsp;West, all of the NEOs are fully vested in the Supplemental 401(k) Match credits presented and will
be paid at a future date or at termination of employment, as elected by the executive subject to the provisions of Section&nbsp;409A of the IRC. Mr.&nbsp;Tillemans and Ms.&nbsp;West will vest in this benefit upon completion of two years of
employment. If vested, they will receive payment for this benefit at termination of employment subject to the provisions of Section&nbsp;409A of the IRC. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Effective January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2007, we began crediting the deferred compensation accounts of all employees hired on or after January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2007,
including eligible NEOs, with the amount of Core Retirement Contributions that exceed the limits established by the IRS for contribution to the 401(k) plan. These amounts are credited in the first quarter of the year after they are earned. As shown
in the footnotes to the 2017 Summary Compensation Table, these amounts are designated as &#147;Supplemental Core Retirement Contribution&#148; and are included as &#147;All Other Compensation&#148; in the year earned. These amounts also are included
in Column&nbsp;(c) of the 2017 <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-Qualified</FONT> Deferred Compensation Table in the year earned. Mmes. Little and West and Messrs.&nbsp;O&#146;Day and Tillemans are eligible for a Supplemental CRC credit for 2017.
Ms.&nbsp;Little and Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day are fully vested in this benefit and will receive payment at termination of employment subject to the provisions of Section&nbsp;409A of the IRC. Mr.&nbsp;Tillemans and Ms.&nbsp;West will vest in this benefit
upon completion of two years of employment. If vested, they will receive payment for this benefit at termination of employment subject to the provisions of Section&nbsp;409A of the IRC. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">73 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Mmes. Little and West and Messrs.&nbsp;O&#146;Day and Tillemans are also eligible to participate in our
DC&nbsp;SERP, a part of the Deferred Compensation Plan. The DC&nbsp;SERP provides annual allocations to the Deferred Compensation Plan equal to a percentage of compensation determined by the Compensation Committee in its sole discretion. In order to
receive the annual DC&nbsp;SERP allocation, an executive must (i)&nbsp;defer into the 401(k) plan the maximum amount allowed by the Company or the IRS and (ii)&nbsp;be employed on the last day of the plan year, unless the executive terminates
employment after age 55 and completion of five years of continuous employment preceding termination, dies or becomes disabled. After completing five years of service with the Company, an executive is vested in 10% increments based on his or her age.
An executive age&nbsp;46 with five years of service is 10% vested and an executive age 55 with five years of service is 100% vested. The annual DC&nbsp;SERP allocation for Mmes. Little and West and Messrs.&nbsp;O&#146;Day and Tillemans is equal to
12.5% of base salary and OHIP award for the calendar year, whether paid or deferred. Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day is 100% vested in his DC&nbsp;SERP benefit, while Mmes. Little and West and Mr.&nbsp;Tillemans are 0% vested because they have not yet completed
five years of continuous employment with the Company. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The following table and explanatory footnotes provide information relating to the activity in the
Deferred Compensation Plan accounts of the NEOs during 2017 and the aggregate balance of the accounts as of December&nbsp;31, 2017: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">Year</FONT><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(1)</SUP></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">($)</FONT></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:3pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt" align="left">&nbsp;</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-TOP:1px solid #3f000b; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #999999; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #999999">&nbsp;</TD>

Supplemental 401(k) Match contributions and the Supplemental CRC earned for 2017. These contributions are included in Column (i)&nbsp;of the 2017 Summary Compensation Table. </TD></TR></TABLE>

<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><B><A NAME="toc498129_39"></A>Potential Payments upon Termination or Change in Control </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">We maintain plans covering our NEOs that will require
us to provide incremental compensation in the event of termination of employment or a Change in Control (as such term is defined in the applicable governing document), provided certain conditions are met. The following narrative takes each
hypothetical termination of employment situation &#150; voluntary resignation, termination for Cause, death, disability, retirement, termination without Cause, and resignation for Good Reason &#150; and a Change in Control of the Company, and
describes the additional amounts, if any, that the Company would pay or provide to the NEOs, or their beneficiaries, as a result. This narrative regarding hypothetical termination events does not include information on benefits the Company would pay
or provide to Mr. Bilbrey upon the occurrence of such events as he was no longer an employee of the Company on December 31, 2017. Instead, the actual payments made to Mr. Bilbrey upon his retirement are described below under the section entitled
&#147;Separation Payments under Retirement Agreement.&#148; </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The narrative below and the amounts shown reflect certain assumptions we have made in
accordance with SEC rules. We have assumed that the termination of employment or Change in Control occurred on December&nbsp;31, 2017, and that the value of a share of our Common Stock on that day was $113.51, the closing price on the NYSE on
December&nbsp;29,&nbsp;2017, the last trading day of 2017. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In addition, in keeping with SEC rules, the following narrative and amounts do not include
payments and benefits which are not enhanced by a qualifying termination of employment or Change in Control. These payments and benefits are referred to as &#147;vested benefits&#148; and include: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Vested benefits accrued under the 401(k) and pension plans; </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Accrued vacation pay, health plan continuation and other similar amounts payable when employment terminates under programs generally applicable to the Company&#146;s salaried employees; </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Vested Supplemental 401(k) Match and Supplemental CRC provided to the NEOs on the same basis as all other employees eligible for Supplemental 401(k) Match and Supplemental CRC; </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-Qualified</FONT> Deferred Compensation Table;&#148; and </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
