 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">75 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><I>Voluntary Resignation (other than a Resignation for Good Reason) </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">We are not obligated to pay amounts over and above vested benefits to a NEO who voluntarily resigns. Vested stock options may not be exercised after the
NEO&#146;s resignation date unless the executive meets retirement eligibility requirements (separation after attainment of age 55 with at least five years of continuous service). </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><I>Termination for Cause </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">If we
terminate a NEO&#146;s employment for Cause, we are not obligated to pay the executive any amounts over and above vested benefits. The NEO&#146;s right to exercise vested stock options expires upon termination for Cause, and amounts otherwise
payable under the DB&nbsp;SERP are subject to forfeiture at the Company&#146;s discretion. In general, a termination will be for Cause if the executive has been convicted of a felony or has engaged in gross negligence or willful misconduct in the
performance of duties, material dishonesty or a material violation of Company policies, including our Code of Ethical Business Conduct, or bad faith actions in the performance of duties not in the best interests of the Company. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><I>Death or Disability </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">If a NEO
dies prior to meeting the vesting requirements under the DB SERP, no benefits are paid. As of December&nbsp;31, 2017, Ms.&nbsp;Buck was fully vested in her DB&nbsp;SERP benefit and her estate would therefore be entitled to a payout of such benefits
in the event of her death. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">If a NEO dies or becomes disabled prior to meeting the vesting requirements under the 401(k) plan or for the Supplemental
401(k) Match, Supplemental CRC or DC SERP benefits, the accrued amounts under those plans become vested. Mr.&nbsp;Tillemans and Ms.&nbsp;West are not fully vested in these benefits. In the event of death or disability, Mr.&nbsp;Tillemans and
Ms.&nbsp;West will receive $92,182 and $85,731, respectively, as a result of vesting. Ms.&nbsp;Little is not fully vested in her DC SERP benefit. In the event of death or disability Ms.&nbsp;Little will receive $353,632 as a result of vesting. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In the event of termination due to disability, long-term disability (&#147;LTD&#148;) benefits are generally payable until age 65, but may extend for longer if
disability benefits begin after age 60, and are offset by other benefits such as Social Security. The maximum amount of the monthly LTD payments from all sources, assuming LTD began on December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2017, is set forth in the table below:
</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><I>Treatment of Stock Options upon Retirement, Death or Disability </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In the event of retirement, death or disability, vested stock options remain exercisable for a period of three or five years, not to exceed the option
expiration date. The exercise period is based upon the terms and conditions of the individual grant. Retirement is defined as separation after attainment of age 55 with at least five years of continuous service. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Options that are not vested at the time of retirement, death or disability will generally vest in full (subject to the exception described in the following
sentence) and the options will remain exercisable for three or five years following termination, depending on the terms and conditions of the grant. Options granted in the year of retirement are prorated based upon the number of full calendar months
worked in that year. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The following table provides the number of unvested stock options as of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2017, that would have become vested
and remained exercisable during the three-year or five-year periods following death or disability, or retirement if applicable, on December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2017, and the value of those options based on the excess of the fair market value of our Common
Stock on December&nbsp;29, 2017, the last trading day of 2017, over the applicable option exercise price. As of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2017, Ms.&nbsp;Buck and Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day were considered retirement eligible based on the provisions of all
outstanding option awards. Because Mmes.&nbsp;Little and West and Mr.&nbsp;Tillemans were not considered retirement eligible as of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2017, they would forfeit 60,364 stock options, 24,530 stock options and 13,920 stock options,
respectively, upon voluntary separation. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">

price exceeds $113.51 are not included in the calculations. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><I>Treatment of RSUs upon Retirement, Death or Disability
</I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Upon retirement, any unvested RSUs are forfeited. Unvested RSUs will vest in full upon death or disability. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">77 </P>

<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The following table provides the number of unvested RSUs that would have vested on December&nbsp;31, 2017,
if the executive&#146;s employment terminated that day due to death or disability: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">


<TR>

<P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><I>Treatment of PSUs upon Retirement, Death or Disability </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In general, in the event of retirement, death or disability, any unvested contingent PSUs are prorated based on the number of full or partial months worked in
each of the open PSU cycles. Any remaining unvested contingent PSUs not prorated are forfeited. The special PSU award granted to Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day in 2017 is subject to forfeiture in the event of his retirement. The following table provides the
total number of contingent PSUs each NEO would be entitled to if the executive&#146;s employment ended on December&nbsp;31, 2017 due to death or disability, or retirement if applicable. As of December&nbsp;31, 2017, Ms.&nbsp;Buck and
Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day were considered retirement eligible based on the provisions of all open PSU cycles, with the exception of Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day&#146;s special PSU award. Because Mmes. Little and West and Mr.&nbsp;Tillemans were not considered
retirement eligible as of December&nbsp;31, 2017, they would forfeit all of their contingent PSUs upon voluntary separation. Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day would forfeit 9,341 contingent PSUs upon voluntary separation per the provisions of his special PSU
award agreement. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><I>Termination without Cause; Resignation for Good Reason </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Under Ms.&nbsp;Buck&#146;s employment agreement and the EBPP&nbsp;3A, as applicable, we have agreed to pay severance benefits if we terminate a NEO&#146;s
active employment without Cause or if the NEO resigns </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">78 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">
from active employment for Good Reason, in each case as defined in the applicable document. Severance benefits consist of a lump sum payment calculated as a multiple of base salary and target
OHIP as well as continuation of health and welfare benefits and financial planning and tax preparation benefits for a set period of time, as shown in the table below. Additionally, all NEOs would be entitled to receive a pro rata payment of the OHIP
award, if any, earned for the year in which termination occurs, as well as outplacement services up to $35,000. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">If a NEO has not met retirement eligibility requirements and his or her employment is terminated for reasons other than for
Cause, or if the NEO terminates for Good Reason, he or she will be eligible to exercise all vested stock options and a prorated portion of his or her unvested stock options held on the date of separation from service for a period of 120 days
following separation. If the NEO is age 55 or older with five or more years of continuous service and his or her employment is terminated for reasons other than for Cause, or if the NEO terminates for Good Reason, the NEO will be entitled to
exercise any vested stock options until the earlier of three or five years (based on the provisions of the individual grant) from the date of termination or the expiration of the options. In addition, if a NEO&#146;s employment is terminated for
reasons other than for Cause, or if the NEO terminates for Good Reason, the NEO will vest in a prorated portion of any unvested RSUs held on the date of separation from service. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The following table provides the incremental amounts that would have been payable to each NEO had his or her employment terminated on
December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2017, under circumstances entitling the NEO to severance benefits as described above: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">For information with respect to stock options and RSUs held by each NEO as of December&nbsp;31, 2017, refer
to the Outstanding Equity Awards at 2017 Fiscal-Year End Table. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><I>Change in Control </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The EBPP&nbsp;3A provides for the vesting and payment of the following benefits to each of the NEOs upon a Change in Control: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">An OHIP payment for the year in which the Change in Control occurs, calculated as the greater of target or the estimated payment based on actual performance through the date of the Change in Control; </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">To the extent not vested, full vesting of benefits accrued under the DB&nbsp;SERP and the Deferred Compensation Plan; and </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">To the extent not vested, full vesting of benefits under the 401(k) and pension plans. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Under our EICP, awards
are continued as qualifying replacement awards after a Change in Control, and therefore, no accelerated vesting or payment will occur for such awards because of the Change in Control. In the event of termination of employment within two years
following the Change in Control for any reason other than termination for Cause or resignation without Good Reason, the replacement awards will vest and become payable as described below. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The following table and explanatory footnotes provide information with respect to the incremental amounts that would have vested and become payable on
December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2017, if a Change in Control occurred on that date. All unvested awards would continue as qualifying replacement awards, and therefore are not included in the table below: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #3f000b; padding-left:8pt">
<P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Ms.&nbsp;West</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</TD>

<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(1)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">With the exception of Ms.&nbsp;Little, the amount of the OHIP award earned for 2017 was greater than target. Therefore, no incremental amount attributable to that program would have been payable upon a Change in
Control. For Ms.&nbsp;Little, reflects the difference between the target amount and the actual amount earned. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(2)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Reflects the full vesting value of DB SERP benefits and more favorable early retirement discount factors as provided under the EBPP 3A. Ms.&nbsp;Buck is fully vested in her DB SERP benefit and the more favorable early
retirement factors do not apply to the CEO, so no additional benefit is applicable. For Ms.&nbsp;West and Mr.&nbsp;Tillemans, the amount includes the vesting of their respective DC SERP benefit, 401(k), Supplemental 401(k) Match, CRC and
Supplemental CRC. For Ms.&nbsp;Little, the amount includes the vesting of her DC SERP benefit. Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day is fully vested in his DC SERP benefit so no additional benefit is applicable. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(3)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">For any given executive, the total payments made in the event of termination after a Change in Control would be reduced to the &#147;safe harbor&#148; limit under IRC Section&nbsp;280G if such reduction would result in
a greater <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">after-tax</FONT> benefit for the executive. </TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">80 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><I>Termination without Cause or Resignation for Good Reason after Change in Control
</I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">If a NEO&#146;s employment is terminated by the Company without Cause or by the NEO for Good Reason within two years after a Change in Control,
we pay severance benefits under the EBPP 3A to assist the NEO in transitioning to new employment. These severance benefits as of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2017, consist of: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">A lump sum cash payment equal to two (or, if less, the number of full and fractional years from the date of termination to the executive&#146;s 65<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">th</SUP> birthday, but not
less than one) times: </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="8%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top"><FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:WINGDINGS">&#161;</FONT></SUP>&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top"></SUP>The executive&#146;s base salary; and </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="8%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top"><FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:WINGDINGS">&#161;</FONT></SUP>&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top"></SUP>The highest OHIP award payment paid or payable during the three years preceding the year of the Change in Control (but not less than the OHIP target award for the
year of the termination); </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">For replacement PSU awards, full vesting of PSUs for the performance cycle ending in the year of the Change in Control. The cash payment will be based upon the greater of target or actual performance through the date of
the Change in Control, with each PSU valued at the highest closing price for our Common Stock during the 60 days prior to the Change in Control; </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">For replacement PSU awards, full vesting of outstanding PSUs at target that are in the second year of the performance cycle and prorated vesting of outstanding PSUs at target that are in the first year of the
performance cycle at the time of the Change in Control; </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">For replacement stock options and RSU awards (including accrued cash credits equivalent to dividends that would have been earned had the executive held Common Stock instead of RSUs), full vesting of all unvested stock
options and RSUs; </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Continuation of medical, dental, vision and life benefits for 24 months (or, if less, the number of months until the executive attains age 65, but not less than 12 months), or payment of the value of such benefits if
continuation is not permitted under the terms of the applicable plan; </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">For executives who do not participate in the pension plan, a lump sum equal to the CRC rate times the sum of their base salary and OHIP earnings times the number of years in their severance period (two, or, if less, the
number of full and fractional years from the date of termination to the executive&#146;s 65<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">th</SUP> birthday, but not less than one). IRS limitations imposed on the 401(k) and pension plans will not
apply for this purpose; </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Outplacement services up to $35,000 and reimbursement for financial counseling and tax preparation services for two years; </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">An enhanced matching contribution cash payment equal to the 401(k) matching contribution rate of 4.5% multiplied by the executive&#146;s base salary and last OHIP payment calculated as if such amounts were paid during
the years in the executive&#146;s severance period. For this purpose, the IRS limitations imposed on the 401(k) plan do not apply; </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">For executives who participate in the DB&nbsp;SERP, an enhanced benefit reflecting an additional two years of credit; and </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">For executives who participate in the DC&nbsp;SERP, an enhanced benefit reflecting a cash payment equal to the applicable percentage rate multiplied by his or her base salary and last OHIP payment calculated as if such
amounts were paid during the years in the executive&#146;s severance period. </TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">81 </P>

</DIV></Center>

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">For the performance cycle ending December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2019, and for Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day&#146;s special PSU award, <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-third</FONT> of the contingent target units awarded, at target
performance, with a value per PSU of $115.45 the highest closing price for our Common Stock on the NYSE during the last 60 days of 2017. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:4%; font-size:7.5pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Because Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day and Ms.&nbsp;Buck were retirement eligible as of December&nbsp;31, 2017, as of that date they had already vested
in a portion of the PSU awards for the performance cycles ending December&nbsp;31, 2018 and December&nbsp;31, 2019. Accordingly, with respect to these NEOs, the amount for the performance cycle ending December&nbsp;31, 2018, reflects only
(i)&nbsp;an incremental payment of the portion of the PSU award that would vest upon termination following a Change in Control (<I>i.e.</I> 1/3 of the total award) and (ii)&nbsp;an incremental benefit equal to the difference between a value per PSU
of $115.45 the highest closing price of our Common Stock on the NYSE during the last 60 days of 2017, and a value per PSU of $113.51 the closing price of our Common Stock on the NYSE on December&nbsp;29, 2017, the last trading day of 2017, while the
amount for the performance cycle ending December&nbsp;31, 2019, reflects only an incremental benefit equal to the difference between a value per PSU of $115.45 and a value per PSU of $113.51. </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(2)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Reflects the value of unvested options that would vest upon the executive&#146;s employment termination following a Change in Control based on the excess, if any, of the value of our Common Stock of $113.51 on
December&nbsp;29, 2017, the last trading day of 2017, over the exercise price for the options. Information regarding unvested options as of December&nbsp;31, 2017 can be found in the Outstanding Equity Awards at 2017 Fiscal-Year End Table.
</TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

of DC SERP, CRC, Supplemental CRC, 401(k) Match and Supplemental 401(k) Match that would have been paid had they remained employees for 24 months after their termination. For Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day, the value reflects the amounts of DC SERP, CRC,
Supplemental CRC, 401(k) Match and Supplemental 401(k) Match that would have been paid had he remained an employee for 12 months after his termination. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

greater <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">after-tax</FONT> benefit for the executive. </TD></TR></TABLE>

Ratio Disclosure </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The annual total
compensation of our CEO for fiscal year 2017 was $10,600,386. This differs from the value reported in the Summary Compensation Table included in this Proxy Statement because Ms.&nbsp;Buck did not become CEO until March&nbsp;1, 2017. In accordance
with the requirements set forth in Item 402(u) of Regulation <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">S-K,</FONT> we adjusted Ms.&nbsp;Buck&#146;s compensation to reflect what she would have earned if she had been CEO for the entire fiscal year. The median
of the annual total compensation for all employees, excluding the CEO, for fiscal year 2017 was $28,173. As a result, we estimate that the ratio of the annual total compensation of our CEO to the annual total compensation of the median employee for
fiscal year 2017 was 376 to 1. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">We identified the median employee using base salary, including overtime, earned in the first nine months of 2017 for all
employees, excluding our CEO, as of October&nbsp;10, 2017, the second Tuesday in October in 2017. After identifying the median employee, we calculated annual total compensation for such employee using the same methodology used for calculating the
total compensation of our NEOs as set forth in the Summary Compensation Table. </P>

NAMED EXECUTIVE </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><B>OFFICER COMPENSATION </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:18pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" ALIGN="center">

<TD VALIGN="middle" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #3f000b; padding-left:8pt"><FONT STYLE="font-size:40pt" COLOR="#3f000b">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>

<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">The Board of Directors unanimously recommends that stockholders</FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">vote <B>FOR</B> approval, on a
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-binding</FONT> advisory basis, of the compensation</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><FONT
 COLOR="#FFFFFF">of the Company&#146;s named executive officers</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt" align="left">&nbsp;</P></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In accordance with the Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act and related SEC rules, and as required under
Section&nbsp;14A of the Exchange Act, we are providing stockholders an opportunity to conduct an advisory vote regarding the compensation of our NEOs as disclosed in this Proxy Statement. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Prior to submitting your vote, we encourage you to read our Compensation Discussion&nbsp;&amp; Analysis and the accompanying executive compensation tables for
details about our executive compensation program, including information about the 2017 compensation of our NEOs. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">As discussed in more detail in the
Compensation Discussion&nbsp;&amp; Analysis, we believe our executive compensation program is competitive and governed by <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pay-for-performance</FONT></FONT> principles. We emphasize
compensation opportunities that reward results. Our stock ownership requirements and use of stock-based incentives reinforce the alignment of the interests of our executives with those of our long-term stockholders. In doing so, our executive
compensation program supports our strategic objectives and mission. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Accordingly, we ask you to approve the following resolution at the Annual Meeting:
</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:4%; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">&#147;RESOLVED, that the stockholders of The Hershey Company approve, on an advisory basis, the compensation paid to the Company&#146;s
named executive officers, as disclosed in the Proxy Statement for the 2018 Annual Meeting of Stockholders pursuant to the SEC&#146;s compensation disclosure rules, including the Compensation Discussion&nbsp;&amp; Analysis, the Executive Compensation
Tables and the related narrative discussion.&#148; </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Because your vote is advisory, it will not be binding upon the Board. However, as noted in the
Compensation Discussion&nbsp;&amp; Analysis, the Compensation Committee and the Board will, as deemed appropriate, take into account the outcome of the vote when considering future decisions affecting executive compensation. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The affirmative vote of the holders of at least a majority of the shares of Common Stock and Class&nbsp;B Common Stock (voting together as a class) represented
at the Annual Meeting, in person or by proxy, is required to approve this proposal. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">84 </P>

<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><B><A NAME="toc498129_43"></A>SECTION 16(a) BENEFICIAL OWNERSHIP
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><B>REPORTING COMPLIANCE </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Section&nbsp;16(a) of the Exchange Act requires our directors and executive officers, as well as any person who is the beneficial owner of more than 10% of
our outstanding Common Stock, to file reports with the SEC and NYSE showing their ownership and changes in ownership of the Company&#146;s securities. Copies of these reports also must be furnished to us. Based on an examination of these reports and
on written representations provided to us, it is our opinion that all reports for 2017 were timely filed. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><B><A NAME="toc498129_44">
</A>CERTAIN TRANSACTIONS AND RELATIONSHIPS </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Item&nbsp;404 of SEC Regulation <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">S-K</FONT> requires that we
disclose any transaction or series of similar transactions, or any currently proposed transaction(s), in which (i)&nbsp;the Company was or is to be a participant, (ii)&nbsp;the amount involved exceeds $120,000 and (iii)&nbsp;any of the following
persons had or will have a direct or indirect material interest: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Our directors or nominees for director; </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Persons owning more than 5% of any class of our outstanding voting securities; or </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">The immediate family members of any of the persons identified in the preceding three bullets. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT
 COLOR="#3f000b"><B>Policies and Procedures Regarding Transactions with Related Persons&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Board has adopted a written Related Person Transaction Policy that governs the review, approval or ratification of related person transactions. The Related
Person Transaction Policy may be viewed on the Investors section of our website at <I>www.thehersheycompany.com</I>. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Under the Related Person Transaction
Policy, each related person transaction, and any significant amendment or modification to a related person transaction, must be reviewed and approved or ratified by a committee of our Board composed solely of independent directors who have no
interest in the transaction. We refer to each such committee as a Reviewing Committee. The Related Person Transaction Policy also permits the disinterested members of the full Board to act as a Reviewing Committee. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Board has designated the Governance Committee as the Reviewing Committee primarily responsible for the administration of the Related Person Transaction
Policy. In addition, the Board has designated special Reviewing Committees to oversee certain transactions involving the Company and Hershey Trust Company, Milton Hershey School, the Milton Hershey School Trust and companies owned by or affiliated
with any of the foregoing. Finally, the Related Person Transaction Policy provides that the Compensation Committee will review and approve, or review and recommend to the Board for approval, any employment relationship or transaction involving an
executive officer of the Company and any related compensation. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">When reviewing, approving or ratifying a related person transaction, the Reviewing
Committee will examine all material facts about the related person&#146;s interest in, or relationship to, the transaction, including the approximate dollar value of the transaction. If the related person transaction involves an outside director or
nominee for director, the Reviewing Committee also may consider whether the transaction would compromise the director&#146;s status as an &#147;independent director,&#148; &#147;outside director&#148; or
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">&#147;non-employee</FONT> director&#148; under the Board&#146;s Corporate Governance Guidelines, the NYSE Rules, the Code or the Exchange Act. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">85 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><B>Transactions with Hershey Trust Company, Milton Hershey School and the Milton
Hershey School Trust </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">During 2017,
there were no transactions with the Company in which any executive officer, director or nominee for director, or any of their immediate family members, had a direct or indirect material interest that would need to be disclosed pursuant to
Item&nbsp;404 of SEC&nbsp;Regulation <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">S-K,</FONT> nor were any such transactions planned. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In any given year, we may engage
in certain transactions with Hershey Trust Company, Milton Hershey School, the Milton Hershey School Trust and companies owned by or affiliated with any of the foregoing. These transactions are typically immaterial, ordinary-course transactions that
do not constitute related person transactions. However, from time to time we may also engage in related person transactions with Hershey Trust Company, Milton Hershey School, the Milton Hershey School Trust and/or their subsidiaries and affiliates.
Under the Board&#146;s Corporate Governance Guidelines, a special Reviewing Committee normally composed of the directors elected by the holders of the Common Stock voting separately as a class reviews and makes recommendations to the Board regarding
these transactions. The Corporate Governance Guidelines also authorize the independent directors having no affiliation with Hershey Trust Company, Milton Hershey School, the Milton Hershey School Trust or their affiliates to designate a different
special Reviewing Committee to review these transactions. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Effective August&nbsp;24, 2017, the Company entered into a Stock Purchase Agreement with Hershey
Trust Company, as trustee for the Milton Hershey School Trust, pursuant to which the Company agreed to purchase 1,500,000 shares of the Company&#146;s common stock from Hershey Trust Company at a price equal to $106.01 per share, for a total
purchase price of $159,015,000. The transaction was approved by the independent directors of the Company&#146;s Board having no affiliation with Hershey Trust Company, Milton Hershey School, the Milton Hershey School Trust or their affiliates. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Company was not a participant in any other transactions in 2017, and does not currently contemplate being a participant in any transactions in 2018, with
any stockholder owning more than 5% of any class of the Company&#146;s outstanding voting securities that would need to be disclosed pursuant to Item&nbsp;404 of SEC Regulation <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">S-K.</FONT> </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">During 2017, we engaged in transactions in the ordinary course of our business with Hershey Trust Company, Milton Hershey School and companies affiliated with
Hershey Trust Company, Milton Hershey School and the Milton Hershey School Trust. These transactions involved the sale and purchase of goods and services as well as the leasing of real estate at market rates. The transactions were primarily with
Hershey Entertainment&nbsp;&amp; Resorts Company, a company that is owned by the Milton Hershey School Trust. All sales and purchases were made on terms and at prices we believe were generally available in the marketplace and were in amounts that
were not material to us or to Hershey Entertainment&nbsp;&amp; Resorts Company. Therefore, these transactions did not require approval under our Related Person Transaction Policy. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Although our transactions with Hershey Trust Company, Milton Hershey School and the companies affiliated with each of the foregoing and with the Milton Hershey
School Trust (including Hershey Entertainment&nbsp;&amp; Resorts Company) are either immaterial or otherwise not required to be disclosed under Item&nbsp;404 of SEC Regulation <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">S-K,</FONT> because of our relationship
with these entities, we have elected to disclose the aggregate amounts of our purchase and sale transactions with these entities for your information. In this regard: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Our total sales to these entities in 2017 were approximately $1.5&nbsp;million; and </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Our total purchases from these entities in 2017 were approximately $2.5&nbsp;million. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">We do not expect the
types of transactions or the amount of payments to change materially in 2018. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">86 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">From January&nbsp;1, 2017 through May&nbsp;31, 2017, the Company leased to Hershey Entertainment &amp;
Resorts Company a portion of a building owned and occupied by the Company in Hershey, Pennsylvania. The leased area consisted of approximately 67,500 square feet of storage space in the building that was not being utilized by the Company. The lease
was first entered into on January&nbsp;1, 2011, and had a term of one year. The lease permitted Hershey Entertainment&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;Resorts Company to renew the lease for subsequent <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-year</FONT> terms and, if
space was available, to request an increase in the area occupied. Hershey&nbsp;Entertainment&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;Resorts Company had renewed the lease for additional <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-year</FONT> terms each year since 2012. The lease
was on terms we believe were generally available in the marketplace and was not material to us or Hershey Entertainment&nbsp;&amp; Resorts Company. Rent during 2017 was $123,750, which included a pro rata allocation of utilities, insurance,
maintenance and other operating costs. This lease terminated May&nbsp;31, 2017. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Effective June&nbsp;1, 2017, the Company entered into a new lease with
Hershey Entertainment&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;Resorts Company for a portion of a separate building owned and occupied by the Company in Hershey, Pennsylvania. The new leased area consists of approximately 17,660 square feet of storage space in the building
that is not being utilized currently by the Company. The lease permits Hershey Entertainment&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;Resorts Company to renew the lease for subsequent <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-year</FONT> terms and, if space is available, to
request an increase in the area occupied. The lease is on terms we believe are generally available in the marketplace and is not material to us or Hershey Entertainment&nbsp;&amp; Resorts Company. Rent during 2017 was $40,692 and for 2018 is
expected to be $69,757, which amounts include a pro rata allocation of utilities, insurance, maintenance and other operating costs. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><FONT
 COLOR="#3f000b"><B><A NAME="toc498129_45"></A>COMPENSATION COMMITTEE INTERLOCKS </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><B>AND INSIDER
PARTICIPATION </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Mmes.&nbsp;Haben and Koken and Messrs. Malcolm, Mead, Palmer, Ridge and Shedlarz served as members of our Compensation Committee
at various times during 2017. None of the members of our Compensation Committee served as one of our officers or employees during 2017 or at any time in the past, and neither they nor any other director served as an executive officer of any entity
for which any of our executive officers served as a director or member of its compensation committee. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">None of the members of our Compensation Committee
has a relationship with us that is required to be disclosed under Item&nbsp;404 of SEC Regulation <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">S-K.</FONT> </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><B><A NAME="toc498129_46"></A>OTHER MATTERS </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><B>Householding of Proxy Materials&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The SEC has adopted rules that allow us to send in a
single envelope our Notice of Internet Availability of Proxy Materials or a single copy of our proxy solicitation and other required annual meeting materials to two or more stockholders sharing the same address. We may do this only if the
stockholders at that address share the same last name or if we reasonably believe that the stockholders are members of the same family. If we are sending a Notice of Internet Availability of Proxy Materials, the envelope must contain a separate
notice for each stockholder at the shared address. Each Notice of Internet Availability of Proxy Materials must contain a unique control number that each stockholder will use to gain access to our proxy materials and vote online. If we are mailing a
paper copy of our proxy materials, the rules require us to send each stockholder at the shared address a separate proxy card. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">87 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">We believe this rule is beneficial both to our stockholders and to the Company. Our printing and postage
costs are lowered anytime we eliminate duplicate mailings to the same household. However, stockholders at a shared address may revoke their consent to the householding program and receive their Notice of Internet Availability of Proxy Materials in a
separate envelope, or, if they have elected to receive a full copy of our proxy materials in the mail, receive a separate copy of these materials. If you have elected to receive paper copies of our proxy materials and want to receive a separate copy
of these materials for our 2018 Annual Meeting, please call our Investor Relations Department, toll free, at <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">(800)&nbsp;539-0261.</FONT> If you consented to the householding program and wish to revoke your consent
for future years, simply call, toll free, <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">(866)&nbsp;540-7095,</FONT> or write to Broadridge, Householding Department, 51&nbsp;Mercedes Way, Edgewood, New York 11717. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT COLOR="#3f000b"><B>Information Regarding the 2019 Annual Meeting of Stockholders </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The 2019 Annual Meeting of Stockholders is expected to
be held on May&nbsp;1, 2019. To be eligible for inclusion in the proxy materials for the 2019 Annual Meeting of Stockholders, a stockholder proposal must be received by our Corporate Secretary by no later than November&nbsp;22, 2018, and must comply
in all respects with applicable rules of the SEC. Stockholder proposals should be addressed to The Hershey Company, c/o Corporate Secretary, 100 Crystal A Drive, Hershey, Pennsylvania 17033-0810. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">A stockholder may present a proposal not included in our proxy materials from the floor of the 2019 Annual Meeting of Stockholders only if our Corporate

STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:0.5pt" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Wednesday, May&nbsp;2, 2018 10:00 a.m. EDT </FONT><br><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:0.5pt" COLOR="#FFFFFF">GIANT Center </FONT><br><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:0.5pt" COLOR="#FFFFFF">550 West Hersheypark Drive Hershey, PA 17033 </FONT><br><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:0.5pt" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Presenting this Admission Ticket at </FONT><br><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:0.5pt" COLOR="#FFFFFF">HERSHEY&#146;S CHOCOLATE WORLD Attraction entitles you to 25% off selected items from 9:00 a.m. until 6:00 p.m. EDT on May&nbsp;2, 2018. </FONT><br><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:0.5pt" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Offer good on May&nbsp;2, 2018, only. </FONT><br><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:0.5pt" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Important Notice Regarding the Availability of Proxy
Materials for the 2018 Annual Meeting of Stockholders to be held on May&nbsp;2, 2018: </FONT><br><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:0.5pt" COLOR="#FFFFFF">The Notice of 2018 Annual Meeting and Proxy Statement, 2017 Annual Report to
Stockholders and proxy card are available at www.proxyvote.com. </FONT><br><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:0.5pt" COLOR="#FFFFFF">FOLD AND DETACH HERE </FONT><br><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:0.5pt" COLOR="#FFFFFF">FOLD AND DETACH HERE </FONT><br><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:0.5pt" COLOR="#FFFFFF">E38981-P02672-Z71788 </FONT><br><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:0.5pt" COLOR="#FFFFFF">THE HERSHEY COMPANY </FONT><br><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:0.5pt" COLOR="#FFFFFF">STOCKHOLDER&#146;S PROXY AND VOTING INSTRUCTION CARD </FONT><br><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:0.5pt" COLOR="#FFFFFF">The undersigned hereby appoints M. G. Buck and K. S. Purcell, and each of them, as proxies, with full power of substitution, to attend The Hershey Company (the &#147;Company&#148;)
Annual Meeting of Stockholders to be held at 10:00 a.m. EDT, May&nbsp;2, 2018, at GIANT Center, 550 West Hersheypark Drive, Hershey, Pennsylvania, or at any adjournment thereof (&#147;Annual Meeting&#148;), and to vote all of the undersigned&#146;s
shares of the Company&#146;s Common Stock in the manner directed on the reverse side of this card. The shares represented by this proxy, when executed properly, will be voted in the manner directed. If direction is not given but the card is signed,
this proxy will be voted FOR the election of all nominees under Proposal 1, FOR Proposal 2 and FOR Proposal 3 as set forth on the reverse side, and in the discretion of the proxies with respect to such other business as may properly come before the
meeting. </FONT><br><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:0.5pt" COLOR="#FFFFFF">SPECIAL INFORMATION for participants in The Hershey Company 401(k) Plan (&#147;401(k) Plan&#148;) and The Hershey Company Puerto Rico 401(k) Plan
(&#147;PR 401(k) Plan&#148;): This proxy also provides voting instructions for shares held on the record date for the Annual Meeting by Vanguard Fiduciary Trust Company (&#147;Vanguard&#148;),* as trustee of the 401(k) Plan or as custodian appointed
by Banco Popular de Puerto Rico, trustee of the PR 401(k) Plan, as applicable. If you are a participant in either plan, this paragraph (and not the paragraph above) applies with respect to voting these plan shares. By marking and returning this
card, you will direct Vanguard (i)&nbsp;how to vote the shares of Common Stock allocated to your account in that plan and (ii)&nbsp;how to vote a portion of the shares of Common Stock allocated to the accounts of other participants in that plan who
have not submitted voting instructions by the voting deadline. If Vanguard receives your properly marked and executed card on or before April&nbsp;27, 2018, Vanguard will vote these shares in the manner directed by you. If direction is not given or
is received after April&nbsp;27, 2018, Vanguard will vote these shares in the 401(k) Plan or PR 401(k) Plan, as applicable, in the same proportion, respectively, as the final aggregate vote of the 401(k) Plan or PR 401(k) Plan participants who
submitted timely votes on the matter. </FONT><br><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:0.5pt" COLOR="#FFFFFF">This proxy is solicited on behalf of the Board of Directors pursuant to a separate Notice of 2018 Annual Meeting and Proxy
Statement dated March&nbsp;22, 2018, receipt of which is hereby acknowledged. The shares of Common Stock represented by this proxy shall be entitled to one vote for each such share held. Except with regard to voting separately as a class on the
election of M. K. Haben and W. L. Schoppert, shares of Common Stock will vote together with shares of Class&nbsp;B Common Stock without regard to class. </FONT><br><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:0.5pt" COLOR="#FFFFFF">THIS PROXY
AND VOTING INSTRUCTION CARD IS CONTINUED ON THE REVERSE SIDE. </FONT><br><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:0.5pt" COLOR="#FFFFFF">*Vanguard Fiduciary Trust Company, in its capacity as trustee or custodian, has appointed Broadridge
as agent to tally the vote. </FONT></P>
